    <h2>How Much of the Earth's Gold is Assumed Unmined?</h2>
    <p>Gold has fascinated humanity for millennia, not just for its value but for its rarity. Geologists and mining experts estimate that there are roughly <strong>190,000 metric tons</strong> of gold that has been mined in recorded history. However, this is only a fraction of the gold that exists below the Earth's surface.</p>
    <p>Estimates suggest that the Earth contains between <strong>50,000 and 100,000 metric tons</strong> of gold that remains unmined and potentially recoverable using current technologies. These reserves are typically found in hard-to-access locations, such as deep underground or beneath ocean floors. Factors like mining cost, technological limitations, and environmental regulations play a role in determining how much of this gold can be feasibly extracted.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How Much Gold is Left Unmined?</h2>
    <p>The remaining gold is often referred to as unmined or "residual" gold. While precise numbers vary, the consensus among geologists is that there could be up to <strong>50% more gold beneath the surface than has already been mined</strong>. This estimation takes into account both economically viable reserves and deeper deposits that are currently too expensive or risky to extract.</p>
  </section>

