    <h2>How Many Bitcoins Are Left Unmined?</h2>
    <p>Bitcoin, unlike many cryptocurrencies, has a fixed supply capped at 21 million coins. As of 2026, roughly <strong>19.4 million bitcoins</strong> have already been mined. This leaves approximately <strong>1.6 million bitcoins</strong> yet to be mined. These remaining bitcoins are expected to become increasingly difficult to mine due to the halving events and the exponential increase in mining difficulty.</p>

    <h3>How Many Unmined Bitcoins Are Left?</h3>
    <p>The number of unmined bitcoins is important for investors to understand, as it directly affects scarcity and market value. With only about <strong>1.6 million bitcoins remaining</strong>, the supply is approaching its limit. Mining rewards will continue to decrease over time, pushing miners to rely on transaction fees as incentives.</p>

    <h3>How Many Unmined Bitcoins Are There?</h3>
    <p>While estimates might vary slightly due to timing and reporting differences, the consensus is that fewer than <strong>2 million bitcoins remain unmined</strong>. This finite supply is a core principle of Bitcoin's design, intended to preserve its value over time.</p>
